# Product Requirements Document
## My Advance Care Plan — Web App

**Version:** 1.4  
**Platform:** Web (desktop & mobile browser; responsive)  
**Future Platform:** Native iOS app (v2.0)  
**Audience:** Adults planning end-of-life care preferences; family/whānau assisting a loved one; healthcare professionals

---

## 1. Overview

### 1.1 Purpose
A responsive web app that digitises the "My Advance Care Plan" (Our Voice / Tō Tātou Reo) form, enabling users to create, store, update, and share their advance care preferences securely from any browser. Multiple people can manage their plans on a single shared device. The web app serves as the foundation for a future native iOS app.

### 1.2 Problem Statement
The current process relies on a paper-based 4-page form. This creates friction around storage, updates, sharing with healthcare providers, and accessibility in urgent medical situations. A digital solution removes these barriers while preserving the sensitivity and personal nature of the document.

### 1.3 Goals
- Allow multiple people to each maintain their own Advance Care Plan on a shared device
- Allow users to complete the full plan digitally, in their own time, from any device
- Enable easy updates at any point as wishes change
- Provide secure storage with optional sharing (PDF export, healthcare provider forwarding)
- Validate UX assumptions and gather user feedback before committing to a native iOS build

### 1.4 Web-First Rationale
Building a web app first allows the team to:
- Ship faster with a single codebase across all devices
- Gather real user feedback before investing in native development
- Avoid App Store review risk on a health-sensitive product
- Reuse form logic, data models, and PDF generation in the eventual iOS app

---

## 2. Target Users

| User | Description |
|---|---|
| **Primary** | Adults (50+) completing their own advance care plan |
| **Secondary** | Family/whānau assisting a loved one — may manage plans for multiple people on one device |
| **Tertiary** | Healthcare professionals (GPs, nurses, hospice staff) reviewing a plan |

